    "creation_date" : 1344602855,
    "answer_id" : 11901980,
    "question_id" : 11347633,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I've just discovered that the <a href=\"http://davidb.github.com/scala-maven-plugin/index.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">scala-maven-plugin</a> supports both continuous compilation &amp; testing, as well as cross-compilation (Java + Scala). So it's possible to use it over a pure Java build and get all the continuous build goodness.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1525843,
      "reputation" : 583,
      "user_id" : 1424313,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://i.sstatic.net/vRSX1.png?s=256",
      "display_name" : "ailveen",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1424313/ailveen"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 3,
    "last_activity_date" : 1426188804,
    "last_edit_date" : 1426188804,
    "creation_date" : 1424463505,
    "answer_id" : 28637490,
    "question_id" : 11347633,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Recently, I have had a need for a solution to this. Having been learning scala and finding about the goodness of sbt ~test, I want to apply it to <strong>Java projects that do not have continuous test</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Using the scala-maven-plugin that you mentioned, I have created a github seed that <strong>will run Java Junit tests everytime I save a Java source or a Java test</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>Check it out:\n<a href=\"https://github.com/ailveen/maven-scala-java-continuous-test\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://github.com/ailveen/maven-scala-java-continuous-test</a></p>\n\n<p>The project is very simple right now (contains only Java files because that is my current need) but in the future I hope to add scala test (or specs2 or scalacheck) so it works with mixed java and scala files.</p>\n\n<p>Hope you find it useful.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 1742917,
      "reputation" : 580,
      "user_id" : 1593808,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0e7733179a725b09c7963ca8299c4c52?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "iocanel",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1593808/iocanel"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 0,
    "last_activity_date" : 1759915785,
    "creation_date" : 1759915785,
    "answer_id" : 79785286,
    "question_id" : 11347633,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>Jakub, it's been a while. I just bumped into your question and I thought that I'd might share an experiment of mine: <a href=\"https://github.com/sundrio/sundrio/tree/main/examples/continuous-testing-example\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://github.com/sundrio/sundrio/tree/main/examples/continuous-testing-example</a></p>\n<p>To give you some context. Sundrio is a code generation and manipulation framework. Recently, it's ability to model java code got to a level, that I thought that it would be fun to use it in order to perform impact analysis. And here we are. It's experimental, so no promises it will fit your needs.</p>\n<p>If you or anyone else wants to take it for a ride, I'll gladly accept feedback and improve it.</p>\n"
  } ],
